TODO: reconcile free-text gloss entry with first-class STRUCTURED morph feats.

Tension: users expect to gloss by just typing strings (e.g. "NOM.PL") into the
gloss field — fast, familiar — but we also want morphological features as
first-class STRUCTURED data so they're queryable (e.g. Case=Nom|Number=Plur),
not just opaque label strings.

The FST analyze service (services/igt_analyze_fst.py) currently FLATTENS feats:
one affix morpheme per feature tag + a Leipzig gloss STRING. That (a) invents
concatenative morph boundaries that don't exist in fusional forms (Finnish -ja
realizes Pl+Par together), and (b) stores feats only as gloss text — nothing
holds the structured bundle.

Design questions to settle:
- Where do feats live? word-level (UD FEATS) vs per-morpheme.
- One representation or two with a mapping? e.g. a structured feats field
  (metadata.feats / dedicated layer) PLUS a free-text gloss that parses to /
  renders from it, round-tripping "NOM.PL" <-> {Case=Nom, Number=Plur}.
- Editor UX: type a string, get structure; edit structure, see the string.
- How the FST service should write them once a model exists (stop faking
  per-feature morphemes; write the bundle + a portmanteau-aware gloss).

